<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-294-398  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 294 398.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DEC User  March 1990 p49(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Defining standards for fibre optic LANs.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Else, Kevin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The American National Standards Institute is developing the FiberDistributed Data Interface (FDDI) to cope with the demands ofhigh-speed local area networks.andP;  FDDI, currently in the draftstandard phase, is meant for networks faster than 50Mbytes persecond, and operates on the lower two levels of the OSI stack.andO;Fiber-optic LANs will use the None Return to Zero Invertedsignalling method.andP;  For topology, the LANs will use the standardToken Ring scheme, with a second ring carrying data the oppositedirection of the first included for fault tolerant applications.andO;Because of the 100Mbyte/s bandwidth, the FDDI standard will beable to carry both Ethernet and Token Ring traffic over the samecircuit.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsLocal Area NetworksANSIStandardizationFiber Distributed Data Interface Standard.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>